My forecast is largely based on Twitter's market cap history according to companiesmarketcap.com and to some news concerning Elon Musk's attempt on assuming control of the company. The historic market cap indicates that Twitter's market cap has varied more than 20 billion dollars in 4-month periods mora than once and that it has barely been valued under 32 billion dollars since the economic hit of the pandemic started to soothe, so I estimated an 6% chance of it going under that value again. It seemed that a lower number would underestimate the volatility and unpredictability of the companies market cap, but a greater number would leave me little space to establish the basis probability I would build my forecast upon. Looking at Twitter's market cap history chart, there's an evident boom in its value in 2021, that soothens from November on, and a new upheaval since Musk announced its participation on the company. I think the pandemic gave Twitter a new status on the social media market, and it feels to me like a kind of timeless way of communicating online (which is something pretty vague, but I can't imagine Facebook or other forms of textual communicating assuming Twitter's role). Therefore, I estimated an almost 70% chance of its value staying between 32 and 48 billion, a little higher than before the pandemic, but lower than 2021's value because of the economic problems the world is facing, specially inflation, and because 2021's figures seem to me like an irrational overestimate by the market. Musk's move to participate in the company makes my market cap estimation go up for some reasons. I think the success of his attempt must make the value grow in a 4-month period, because the market seems to give his business abilities a good evaluation. I think he won't be able to take control of the company, because of the board's measures to prevent that, but that he will still try to deepen his participation on their decisions. I also think that the board will give to give way to some of his proposals, probably the less controversial ones (which I assume are the safest ones for the company's reputation and the social media's status). That's why I gave a 24% chance of Twitter's market cap being over 48 billion on 26 August.
